comments: Started Fall Trapping Season

Cone was stopped upon arrival due to a large branch. This was likely the cause of our high chinook mortality. We cleared the cone and moved the trap upstream a little so it wouldn't be so close to the rock weir.
Mort appears to have died before being trapped
Trap stopped for Veteran's Day holiday
Trap removed for the winter
Cone stopped spinning - clogged with woody debris and partially sunk due to high flows. Restated around 12:30
Cone stopped spinning - clogged with large log. Restated around 10:30
Cone stopped spinning - clogged with woody debris and partially sunk due to high flows. Stopped trap and pulled closer to bank out of high flows
Started trap - river is coming down
Water came down too much;moved trap out farther into flow; cone put on blocks
Wood blocks removed.
Cone stopped upon arrival - large branch stuck in cone. We moved trap 4-5 ft toward far bank.
Trap moved 3 feet towards near bank (river left)
Log stuck in cone - removed and trap restarted. Trap moved closer to near bank and upriver 3 feet
Large log and lots of debris stuck in cone. Cleared out trap and moved closer to near bank - stopped
Log stuck in cone - removed; cone restarted
Trap stopped by branch - lots of debris in live box
Same transiver file number as previous day (file#35)
Logs stuck in cone - fixed. Trap pulled over to near bamk and stopped.
Trap stopped for the season
